t when the damage is not extensive. In a usual repairing procedure, our dentist removes these infected areas to prevent further progression of the cavitation and its filled to provide protection and restore function of the tooth. A local anaesthesia is administered to make the experience. Teeth cavitation is one of the most prevalent problems in the World. Its very influenced by diet, hygiene habits. It can lead to sensitivities, unbearable pain and further untreated defects can cause complications that may even lead to systemic problems. Dental caries need to be treated at the earliest. These are best treated at an early onset when the damage is not extensive. In a usual repairing procedure, our dentist removes these infected areas to prevent further progression of the cavitation and its filled to provide protection and restore function of the tooth. A local anaesthesia is administered to make the experience non painful and comfortable.\n\nFillings are broadly tooth coloured and metal based. Composite restorations are tooth coloured fillings. They are resin based and can be matched to the existing tooth colour to obtain almost tooth like appearance, and also provides matching strengths. They attach to the tooth surface via a micromechanical bond. Metal fillings are Amalgam fillings. They are less used these days and are provided only in\n\nMetal fillings are Amalgam fillings. They are less used these days and are provided only in situation deemed required.\n\nGlass Ionomer Cements GIC are used for children, in adults involving probe areas and also used as a base under larger fillings. They bond chemically yot he tooth and have properties like white in colour, releases Flouride and is anticariogenic.\n<h2>Root Canal Treatment</h2>\n<p id=\"root-canal\">If the dental caries progresses further into tooth and no intervention is seeked, it can reach the innermost layer of tooth, called Pulp. The pulp contains the nerves innervating and the blood supply of the tooth. Onc